            <TextView
                style="@style/textinfo"
                android:text="Birds can fly and cover large distances, which has allowed them to specialize in a wide variety of habitats which contributed to their high number of species. Despite their ability to fly, birds tend to stay within a specific habitat, which can be helpful in identifying them. " />

            <TextView
                style="@style/textinfo"
                android:text="These habitats include coastal bush, woodland, grassland, montane forest, semi-desert, desert, fynbos, and aquatic habitats. " />

            <TextView
                style="@style/textinfo"
                android:text="Within these habitats, there may be specific areas such as rocky hills or outcrops, patches of denser scrub, water courses lined with trees, or wetlands. " />

            <TextView
                style="@style/textinfo"
                android:text="Understanding the habitat description can provide essential information for identifying a bird or, in some cases, help narrow down available options by eliminating competing possibilities." />

            <TextView
                style="@style/textinfo"
                android:text="For example, you would not expect to see a gull looking for insects in the foliage of a tree in the savanna." />


